\subsubsection{Initial conditions for COVID-19}
once again, to implement the SIR model we required initial conditions and parameters to implement the SIR model. The $R_0$ for COVID-19 is cited to be between 1.4 and 2.5. To stay consistent with out easels data we chose to run the model with three different $R_0$ values of $R_0=1.4$, $R_0= 2.0$, and $R_0=2.5$. We chose the same population size of $N=5000$, again not meaning to represent the total population of Massachusetts but an effective population that participates in an outbreaks with homogeneous mixing. The same $I(0) = 3$ for the COVID model.

\subsubsection{COVID-19 Model Parameters}
The infectious period for COVID-19 is cited to be approximately 7 days, using this approximation we valued our  $\gamma$ at 0.143 per day. again using both $R_0$ and $\gamma$ we could calculate $\betta$. The COVID-19 data was provided in daily cases so the SIR model had to be converted to daily incidence, instead of weekly. 

\section{Results}
\subsection{Measles}
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{r0=12.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 12$}
    \label{$R_0 = 12$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{$R_0 = 12$} shows the implemented SIR model with $R_0 = 12$. This curve looks drastically different from that of the observed. In the first week the case value immediately reaches it's peak, then rapidly decreases around week 2. By week five the case count reaches zero and stays constant for the remaining weeks. It is evident based off this curve that that SIR model did not equality produce the observed data.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R_0=15.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 15$}
    \label{fig:$R_0 = 15$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{fig:$R_0 = 15$} shows the implemented SIR model with $R_0 = 15$. This plot's trend is virtually identical to the plot of $R_0 = 12$. The noticeable differences being that the peak case value was higher, with it being approximately 5,000 cases compared to the $R_0 = 12$ peak of approximately 4,700. The $R_0 = 15$ case values post week one decreased more rapidly with the case value almost at zero imminently after the first week.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R_0=18.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 18$}
    \label{fig:$R_0 = 18$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{fig:$R_0 = 18$} is the least accurate of the three plots. The peak case value is the greatest of them all, which again the peak starts immediately at week 1 and then by week two completely drops to zero. Though none of the three plots accurately represented the observed curve, what became clear is that the smaller the $R_0$ value the better the SIR model performed. With this in mind we then attempted values outside of the cited range to see if we could obtain a more accurate looking plot.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R=2.png}
    \caption{$R_0 = 2$}
    \label{fig:R_0 = 2}
\end{figure}

in Figure\ref{fig:R_0 = 2} we lowered the $R_0$ value significantly to $R_0= 2$, far out of the measles cited range. With such a low value this plot no longer represents an epidemic curve for measles, however, it does show a far more realistic shape. The curve has a rapid growth over the first weeks, reaches a clear peak, and then rapidly decreases to zero. This pattern is similar to that of the observed outbreak curve. This makes it clear that the SIR model better replicates an epidemic curve when it has a lower $R_0$ value. Measles in cited to have one of the highest $R_0$ values of all infectious diseases. This suggests that the SIR model, under homogeneous mixing and constant parameters struggles to produce observed measles outbreak We then look at the results of COVID-19, a infectious diseases with a much lower $R_0 value$. 

\subsection{COVID-19}

Figure\ref{fig:1.4} shows the implemented SIR model for $R_0=1.4$. This curve shows a steady slow growth, the cases increase exponentially for a long period of time and there is no peak within the observation window. Figure\ref{fig:R0=2.0} is the SIR model with $R_0=2.0$. This plot also a slower growth, where the cases increase exponentially. The plot begins to reach a peak, but does not fully reach it during the time period. Figure\ref{fig:2.5} depicts the SIR model for $R_0 = 2.5$. This plot has a fast exponential growth. The peak occurs earlier than the previous plots and can be seen around day 42, then the case count decreases. Though the SIR model had a longer observational window that the observatory data we can still compare the overall patterns of the models to the observed data. Each plot did a relatively good job at depicting the exponential growth phase, unlike measles every plot displayed this. the SIR model with the $R_0=2.5$ had a relatively accurate patter of exponential growth to the observed data. Unlike the others this plot also shows a peak which happens later in the curve, much like the observed outbreak. The SIR model will always output a smooth curve, it does not matter what diseased is modeled. Because the model is a system of concinnous ODEs, it also assumes average behavior of the entire population and does not account for any randomness or reporting delays. Therefore the model can not produce the dips and spikes we see in the observed data. My comparison of the models and the observed data is on qualitative agreement in the outbreak patterns and not matching the exact daily case counts.

\subsection{Discussion}
The SIR model's for measles, did not display accurate outbreak patters. Whereas, the COVID-19 curves did. I believe this is due to the large difference in their $R_0$ values. The effectiveness of the model based of it's basic reputation value is reasonable with the population assumptions. A diseases with high the basic reproduction value, means one infected individual will infect persons than that of an infected individual with a lower value. When we assume a closed homogeneous population, we are assuming the population size is not changing due to births and migration and everyone in the population has equal probability of coming into contact with one another. This aligns with the SIR model for measles showing everyone getting infected immediately. If one person can infect 18 individuals, all of whom have equal probably of coming into contact, it would not take long for everyone to be infected. Then we look at the plots for COVID-19, which showed exponential growth and a peak. On average one infected individual in infecting 1.4 to 2.5 individuals which appeared to allow the SIR model to depict a realistic outbreak patters. These results stand to reason that the $R_0$ value has a large impact of the accuracy of the SIR model. Based off of these results we would that the SIR model can be used for diseases with a lower basic reproduction value, but is not effective for diseases with an increased value. Though it is important to be aware that the model can give an general idea of an outbreak pattern but should certainly not be the sole model used due to its generalizations.

